# Firebase Studio UX/UI Build Specification
## Remote Business Partner
### Template-led UX adaptation guide for public-facing catalogue, service, membership, and knowledge surfaces

> **Purpose of this document**
>
> This file is the implementation brief Firebase Studio must follow when building the public UX/UI for Remote Business Partner.  
> It is intentionally over-explained. Do not compress this into a vague interpretation.  
> The goal is to translate the Limetech Webflow template system into a polished, credible, B2B consulting/product hybrid experience that fits Remote Business Partner, not an insurance brand.

---

## 1. Read this first before building anything

### 1.1 What Firebase Studio is being asked to do
Firebase Studio must build a **visually strong, production-shaped public experience** that uses the **layout language, hierarchy, spacing, and visual rhythm** of the Limetech template system, while replacing the template's industry assumptions, copy patterns, color emphasis, CTA language, and content structure with Remote Business Partner's own business model.

The build is **not** a literal clone of the Limetech site.

It **is** a controlled adaptation of:
- section composition
- card behavior
- visual hierarchy
- navigation rhythm
- page shell consistency
- CTA placement
- whitespace strategy
- motion polish
- responsive behavior
- detail-page structure

### 1.2 What this project is not
Do **not** build:
- an insurance website
- an ecommerce store aesthetic
- a consumer startup aesthetic
- a green/neon color-forward clone of the template
- a page set with inconsistent page shells
- a one-off visual treatment for every content type
- a dashboard-first experience for public content

### 1.3 What this project is
This is a **hybrid consulting + knowledge + member-access platform** with these public catalogue surfaces:
- Home
- DocShare
- Partner Offers
- Knowledge Center
- Services
- Membership

There is also a separate **member operations area** that should remain distinct from the public catalogue experience:
- Portal / dashboard / member operations hub

Public content discovery must happen in the public surfaces.  
The member portal should not become a second public catalogue.

