## 16. Access, gating, and member-state UX

The UX must clearly support three states across public detail pages:

1. `Access available`
2. `Login to access`
3. `Membership required`

## 16.1 Access state panel requirements
Every public detail page that may be gated must show a consistent access panel.

Panel content:
- access badge/state
- explanatory sentence
- primary CTA
- secondary CTA
- optional membership comparison link

## 16.2 Access state copy examples
### Access available
- Available now
- Open resource
- View details

### Login to access
- Sign in to continue
- Access this resource from your account

### Membership required
- Included in Standard and Premium
- Upgrade to access this resource
- Compare membership options

## 16.3 Avoid dark patterns
Do not:
- hide gating until late
- mislabel unavailable content as open
- use misleading button text
- allow broken CTA paths

---

## 17. Component-level UI requirements

## 17.1 Buttons
Primary:
- filled brand color
- high contrast text
- strong hover state
- medium weight label

Secondary:
- outline or soft-fill
- visible border
- accessible contrast

Tertiary:
- text + icon
- used for low-emphasis actions

Button sizes:
- large: hero, CTA bands
- medium: standard content CTAs
- small: filters, utilities

## 17.2 Forms
Forms must use:
- clear labels above fields
- helper/error text below
- visible focus states
- no placeholder-only labels
- grouped spacing
- consistent success/error feedback

## 17.3 Search bars
Search inputs must:
- be large enough to feel primary
- include icon
- support keyboard submit
- show empty-state handling
- provide clear/reset behavior

## 17.4 Accordions
Use for:
- FAQs
- long support explanations
- membership clarifications

Accordions must:
- animate smoothly
- support keyboard navigation
- maintain readable line lengths

## 17.5 Tables
Pricing or comparison tables must:
- remain readable on tablet
- collapse responsibly on mobile
- avoid forcing horizontal scroll where possible
- use row-grouping if necessary

---

## 18. Responsive behavior rules

## 18.1 Desktop
- full asymmetrical hero layouts
- sticky right sidebars on detail pages
- 3-column or 4-column grids where needed
- larger breathing room

## 18.2 Tablet
- collapse hero into 1-column or stacked 2-row layout
- reduce sidebar complexity
- preserve CTA visibility
- grids mostly 2-column

## 18.3 Mobile
- single column
- key CTA above the fold
- sticky sidebars become inline CTA blocks
- filters may use drawers or chips
- knowledge/search remains prominent
- headings must remain punchy and not wrap into unreadable towers of text

## 18.4 Mobile-specific caution
Do not simply stack desktop sections without redesigning spacing and order.  
On mobile, reorder content so users see:
1. the purpose
2. the CTA
3. the value
4. the supporting details

